ting agent guidance for JDK 25**\\n\\nI'm thinking about what to include in the agent guidance regarding JDK 25. It’s important to recommend avoiding tests that try to install or assert the behavior of `SecurityManager`. Although OGNL has an optional `ognl.security.manager` sandbox, it's not a prerequisite. Instead, I should promote the use of standard OGNL expressions and scenarios. If we do cover the optional sandbox, I need to ensure that UnsupportedOperationException is properly handled. This seems critical for clarity.\"}]}"}, {"type": "text", "text": "{\n  \"action\": \"no_action\",\n  \"summary\": \"OGNL is an in-process expression/object-graph navigation library; the resolved artifact already brings its required Javassist runtime dependency transitively and normal meaningful tests do not need Docker, extra Maven dependencies, or mandatory environment/system properties.\",\n  \"deterministic_setup\": [],\n  \"agent_guidance\": \"No extra environment variables or system properties are required. Do not enable `ognl.security.manager` as general setup; it is an optional OGNL sandbox feature. On JDK 25, avoid relying on installing a JVM `SecurityManager` for baseline coverage, or guard such optional tests for unsupported SecurityManager behavior. Prefer normal OGNL usage over POJOs, maps, collections, property access, method calls, constructors, static fields/methods, and expression parsing/evaluation.\",\n  \"risks\": [\n    \"Existing tests that exercise `System.setSecurityManager` may fail on newer JDKs because SecurityManager support is disabled/removed; that is a test design issue, not a deterministic setup requirement.\",\n    \"Tests that intentionally access strongly encapsulated JDK internals may need module-opening JVM arguments, but ordinary OGNL coverage over application fixtures should not require that as workflow preparation.\"\n  ]\n}", "textSignature": "{\"v\":1,\"id\":\"msg_0cc04912c345a507016a41561541848197971658039cfd83b8\",\"phase\":\"final_ans